15":"about 1115","1096":"1096","1171":"1171","1070":"1070","1180":"1180","UM 1094":"about 1094","1159":"1159","1115":"1115","1147":"1147","1113":"1113","1179":"1179","1157":"1157","1145":"1145","1111":"1111","Abt 1090":"about 1090","Mülhausen, Alsace-Lorraine, German Empire":"Mülhausen, Upper Alsace, Alsace-Lorraine, Germany","Hombourg, Haut-Rhin, Großer Osten, Frankreich":"Hombourg, Haut-Rhin, Grand Est, France","Metz, Moselle, Lorraine, France":"Metz, Moselle, France","Metz, Lorraine, Holy Roman Empire":"Metz, Lorraine, Holy Roman Empire","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Metz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from a short form of the female personal name <i>Mechthild</i>, composed of ancient Germanic <i>maht</i> ‘might, strength’ + <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’.","German, French (Alsace and Lorraine), and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from Metz in Lorraine, which took its name from a Gaulish tribe, the <i>Mediomatrici</i>; in the name of the place this became abbreviated to <i>Mettis</i>, hence the modern name.","German: from <i>Mätz</i>, a short form of the personal name <i>Matthias</i> (see   Matthew  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Mette","meanings":["North German: from a pet form of the female personal name <i>Mechthild</i> (see   Metz  ).","North German: occupational name for a miller, from Middle Low German <i>matte</i>, <i>mette</i> ‘dry measure’.","French: topographic name from Old French <i>mete</i> ‘boundary stone, boundary’ (from Latin <i>meta</i> ‘bounded estate’)."]},{"name":"Metzer","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Metz (see   Metz  ).","Dutch: occupational name for a bricklayer, Middle Dutch <i>metsere</i>."]},{"name":"Metts","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Metz  ."]},{"name":"Matthew","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ma(t)thew</i>, a vernacular form of the Greek New Testament name <i>Matthias</i>, <i>Matthaios</i>, which is ultimately from the Hebrew personal name <i>Matityahu</i> ‘gift of God’. This was taken into Latin as <i>Mat(t)hias</i> and <i>Matthaeus</i> respectively, the former being used for the twelfth apostle (who replaced Judas Iscariot) and the latter for the author of the first Gospel. In many European languages this distinction is reflected in different name forms. The commonest vernacular forms of the personal name, including English <i>Matthew</i>, Old French <i>Matheu</i>, Spanish <i>Mateo</i>, Italian <i>Matteo</i>, Portuguese <i>Mateus</i>, Catalan and Occitan <i>Mateu</i> are generally derived from the form <i>Matthaeus</i>. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, including German   Matthias  , Greek   Mathias   and <b>Mattheos</b>, Assyrian/Chaldean   Matti  , Czech <b>Matěj</b>, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian   Matej  . The name <i>Matthew</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Mathai  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Mathew  , see also   Matthews  ."]},{"name":"Metze","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Armin, Gerhard, Gernot.","German:","metronymic from a short form of the personal name <i>Mechthild</i> (see   Metz   1)."]}]},{"name":"Folmar","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Vollmar  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vollmar","meanings":["from <i>folk</i> ‘people’ + <i>mar</i> ‘famous’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Folmar V de Metz was born about 1090, in Metz, Moselle, Lorraine, France as the son of Folmar IV de  Metz. He married Matilda von Dagsburg in 1120. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 3 daughters. He died in 1145, in Hombourg, Haut-Rhin, Grand Est, France, at the age of 56."},"et":{"Abt 1090–1145":"umbes 1090–1145","1090–1145":"1090–1145","1096–1157":"1096–1157","1113–1179":"1113–1179","1115–1180":"1115–1180","–1147":"–1147","–1157":"–1157","–1159":"–1159","–1171":"–1171","1070–1111":"1070–1111","1090":"1090","1120":"1120","25 June 1111":"25. juuni 1111","Abt 1115":"umbes 1115","1096":"1096","1171":"1171","1070":"1070","1180":"1180","UM 1094":"umbes 1094","1159":"1159","1115":"1115","1147":"1147","1113":"1113","1179":"1179","1157":"1157","1145":"1145","1111":"1111","Abt 1090":"umbes 1090","Mülhausen, Alsace-Lorraine, German Empire":"Kreis Mülhausen, Bezirk Oberelsaß, Elsaß-Lothringen, Saksamaa","Hombourg, Haut-Rhin, Großer Osten, Frankreich":"Hombourg, Haut-Rhin, Grand Est, Prantsusmaa","Metz, Moselle, Lorraine, France":"Metz, Moselle, Prantsusmaa","Metz, Lorraine, Holy Roman Empire":"Metz, Lothringen, Heiliges Römisches Reich"},"fi":{"Abt 1090–1145":"noin 1090–1145","1090–1145":"1090–1145","1096–1157":"1096–1157","1113–1179":"1113–1179","1115–1180":"1115–1180","–1147":"–1147","–1157":"–1157","–1159":"–1159","–1171":"–1171","1070–1111":"1070–1111","1090":"1090","1120":"1120","25 June 1111":"25. kesäkuuta 1111","Abt 1115":"noin 1115","1096":"1096","1171":"1171","1070":"1070","1180":"1180","UM 1094":"noin 1094","1159":"1159","1115":"11